of impairment to explore how disability subjectivities create new forms of embodied knowledge and collective consciousness. The focus is on the emergence of new crip/queer subjectivities at work in disability arts, disability studies pedagogy, independent and mainstream disability cinema (e.g., Midnight Cowboy), internet-based medical user groups, anti-normative novels of embodiment (e.g., Richard Powers's The Echo-Maker) and, finally, the labor of living in "non-productive" bodies within late capitalism.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aDisability studies. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxCivil rights. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSocial conditions. 0aDisabilitiesxGovernment policy. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxGovernment policy. 4aElectronic books.1 aSnyder, Sharon L.,d1963-2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher. 0aCorporealities.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.7331366